
[1]shepherd

   SHEP'HERD, n.

   1. A man employed in tending, feeding and gaurding sheep in the
   pasture.

   2. A swain; a rural lover.

   3. The pastor of a parish, church or congregation; a minister of the
   gospel who superintends a church or parish, and gived instruction in
   spiritual things. God and Christ are in Scripture dinominated
   Shepherds, as they lead, protect and govern their people, and provide
   for their wilfare.
